# 4. Deterministic HD structure

The path does not just organize; it defines existence and versioning.

## 4.1 Path convention

```text
m/ledger/{tenantId}/{orgId}/{ledgerId}/{accountId}/{entryType}/{version}

4.2 Example

m/ledger/tenant-a/acme/main-ledger/cash-usd/debit/v1
m/ledger/tenant-a/acme/main-ledger/merchant-payable/credit/v1
m/ledger/tenant-a/acme/main-ledger/revenue/credit/v1
m/ledger/tenant-a/acme/main-ledger/fees/debit/v1

4.3 Meaning

tenantId: isolation boundary,

orgId: organization,

ledgerId: logical book,

accountId: account,

entryType: debit/credit,

version: immutable version.



---

5. Canonical storage

All entries must be normalized before persistence.

5.1 Canonicalization rules

lexicographic key ordering,

string normalization,

UTC timestamps,

numeric normalization,

no duplicate keys,

no implicit fields,

deterministic representation.


5.2 Input example

{
  "currency": "USD",
  "amount": 100.0,
  "accountId": "cash-usd",
  "reference": "PAY_9f2a",
  "note": "  sale payment "
}

5.3 Canonical output

{"accountId":"cash-usd","amount":100,"currency":"USD","note":"sale payment","reference":"PAY_9f2a"}

5.4 Hash

contentHash = sha256(canonicalJson)

This hash uniquely identifies the entry.


---

6. Double-entry accounting

6.1 Structural rule

Every operation must balance:

one debit,

one credit,

same magnitude,

same currency.


6.2 Example: 100 USD captured payment

Entry 1

Debit: cash-in-transit 100

Credit: merchant-payable 100


Entry 2

Debit: merchant-payable 2

Credit: revenue 2


Entry 3

Debit: merchant-payable 98

Credit: merchant-settlement-clearing 98



